Answers to questions:
1. The strategy I used for the "clever" player is trying to create a win streak in the
first row of the board. If, for some reason he fails, he acts like the "whatever" player,
i.e he picks a random available position on the board
The strategy I used for the "genius" player is trying to create a win streak in the third
column of the board. If, for some reason, he fails, he acts like the "whatever" player, i.e
he picks a random available position on the board.

2. An advantage of designing the program in which each of the player's classes implement
a shared interface is that similar methods using these classes avoid duplicate
code (the methods are with a more general purpose and type).
Moreover, if in the future we decide to change the implementation of the classes or add
more types of players, the costumer won't have to change his code(as long as
he refers the players as general players).

The fact that we create a few types of players with a joint interface is based on the
"polymorphism pillar".
Being able to treat the different players as a more general type(player) is based on
the "abstraction pillar".